default– ET/1604478/11 &amp; ET/1600000/12
default 
defaultThe employment tribunal upheld a claim of direct disability discrimination and made a recommendation that the HR managers should receive training ‘relating specifically to the issue of mental health disability’.
defaultWhy v Enfield Grammar School - 3303944/2011
defaultThe employment tribunal upheld a claim for discrimination on grounds of pregnancy and made a wider recommendation that the senior management team and all heads of 
defaultdepartment have training on equal opportunities employment law within 6 months, including the position of women on, and returning from, maternity leave. 
defaultThe Tribunal upheld a claim for victimisation, sexual orientation harassment and religion or belief harassment (managers had called an employee “gay” for not liking football”, and for doing household chores. He was also repeatedly called a “pagan” for not agreeing with statements expressed by Jehovah’s witnesses). They also made a wider 
defaultrecommendation
default, that the Respondent updates its policies on discrimination taking account of the Equality Act 2010 and that the directors and managers of the Samuel Grant Group receive diversity training from a reputable provider, both recommendations to be complied with no later than six months from the date of the judgment.
defaultKerr v O’Hara Brothers Surfacing Ltd. [2013] 
defaultEqLR
default 296
defaultThe Tribunal found the Respondent 
defaultcompany
default liable for age discrimination and age-related harassment and made recommendations including that the Respondents will discuss language within the workplace with their entire workforce and will devise and implement a work 
defaultrostering
default system allowing for individual capacity to be objectively assessed and combined with information on availability and skills.
defaultNcheke
default v Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service [2013] 
defaultEqLR
default 649
defaultThe Tribunal upheld a claim of failure to make reasonable adjustment and recommended that the Respondent’s line managers and HR are to receive adequate training on the Respondent’s own disability leave policy and to ensure that the policy is appropriately communicated to employees.
defaultDixon v Royal Mail Group Limited [2013] 
defaultEqLR
default 1910
defaultIn this case the Respondent accepted that it had unlawfully discriminated against the Claimant because of her pregnancy or maternity. At the remedy hearing the Tribunal made a series of recommendations including that within 28 days of the issue of the Tribunal’s judgment the Respondent shall publish the Tribunal’s written reasons on their internet; the Tribunal noted that it “accepted the Claimant’s contention that bringing the judgment  to the attention of all managers and employees in the Royal Mail would increase their awareness of the risks of discrimination and therefore was likely to reduce the risk of such discrimination occurring to other employees in the future”.
